name: 李老师不是你老师
content:
China suspends imports of some Brazilian soybeans due to detection of pesticides and pests
On January 23, Reuters reported: The Brazilian Ministry of Agriculture issued a statement on the 22nd saying that the General Administration of Customs of China found pesticides and pests during routine inspections of goods, so it suspended soybean imports from the five Brazilian suppliers involved.
Gerlach, president of the US brokerage firm A/C Trading, believes that China may want to slow down the pace of imports from Brazil to give Beijing room to reach a trade agreement with Washington, which may include the purchase of US soybeans.
China buys more than 60% of the world's soybeans, and currently imports more than 70% of its total soybean imports from Brazil, eroding the US market share.
